title: Grateful Dead Live at Southern Star Amphitheater on 1985-08-30
lineage: Cassette Master (Nakamichi CR-7A) > Tascam DA-3000 (DSF 1-bit/5.8 MHz) >KORG AudioGate 4 > Adobe Audition CC 2015 > Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/24
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw, Row Jimmy, CC Rider, Bird Song-> Looks Like Rain-> Deal

Set 2

Scarlet Begonias-> Touch Of Grey, Samson & Delilah-> Drums-> Gimme Some Lovin'-> The Wheel-> The Other One-> Morning Dew, E: Sugar Magnolia

reviews.review_text:
Terrific in Texas '85! It’s easy to see why a lot of mid-80s’ shows fell apart at the seams. This era is commonly referred to as “sloppy”. It strikes me as one of those stretches where they were barely rehearsing, if at all. They weren’t in the studio, or riding the momentum of a new album or surge in popularity. Heroin and Heineken were hovering. Performances were so loose that the band as a unit was susceptible to having bad (or at least not very good) nights. 

However, many times that same looseness could play to their advantage. When everyone was on the same sloppy page, surfing the slapdash thrown-together wave in unison, they could serve up some outstanding performances. Tiger purring and growling away, framed against a warm tapestry of supporting sounds.

Thus, the duality of 1985: 8/24/85 saw what many folks consider to be their worst ever performance. Less than a week later, we get 8/30/85, which is an exquisite, leathery, piping hot Texas special.

It’s a quick one, probably because of the temperature they were operating in. Six-song first set, just three songs pre-drums, a brief 5:40 The Other One… you can actually hear the extreme heat baking into the performance, not unlike Veneta ‘72. Although it’s a short performance, they really make it count. I was drawn to this by the fabulous setlist, which is executed with earnest originality. Too short and consistently strong to cherry-pick. Just enjoy the whole show!

Excellent SBD recording, with real balance and clarity.

This one is really, really good folks.
